J Cell Biochem. 2018;1-9. Abstract The epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) was found to be overexpressed in

several cancers, especially in lung cancers. Finding new effective drug against EGFR is the key to cancer treatment. In this study, the GOLD docking algorithm was used to virtually screen for novel human EGFR inhibitors from the NCI database. Thirty‐ four hit compounds were tested for EGFR‐tyrosine kinase (TK) inhibition. Two potent compounds, 1‐amino‐4‐(4‐[4‐amino‐2‐sulfophenyl]anilino)‐9,10‐dioxoanthra- cene‐2‐sulfonic acid (NSC125910), and nogalamycin N‐oxide (NSC116555) were identified with IC50 values against EGFR‐TK comparable to gefitinib; 16.14 and 37.71 nM, respectively. However, only NSC116555 demonstrated cytotoxic effects against non–small‐cell lung cancer, A549, shown in the cell cytotoxicity assay with an IC50 of 0.19 + 0.01 µM, which was more potent than gefitinib. Furthermore, NSC116555 showed cytotoxicity against A549 via apoptosis in a dose‐dependent manner. Lung cancer remains the leading cause of cancer‐related death responsible for ~1.69 million deaths worldwide as reported by World Health Organization (WHO) in 2015.1 The majority of lung cancer cases are associated with long‐ term smoking, but genetic and environmental factors also play a role. Lung cancer is characterized by uncontrolled cell growth of the lung tissues with two main types of lung cancer categorized into non–small‐cell lung cancer (NSCLC) and small‐cell lung cancer (SCLC). NSCLC accounts for ~80% to 85% of all lung cancers, whereas SCLC contributed to a smaller proportion of cases 10% to 15%.2 Most untreated patients with advanced NSCLC and progressed metastasis were reported to have a median survival period after diagnosis of 4 to 5 months, whereas 1‐year survival rate was observed in less than 10%.3 Both SCLC and NSCLC to chemotherapy, radiation, and adjuvant respond well therapies.4 However, these therapeutic strategies were hindered by the undesirable side effects. Hence, there is a need for alternative therapeutic methods that selectively target cancer cells, for example, selective targeted‐based strategies.

Epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) is a cell‐surface receptor belonging to the ErbB family of tyrosine kinases (TKs)5 and is expressed in many tissue types including normal epithelial, mesenchymal, and neurogenic tissues.6 Various mechanisms can cause EGFR expression aberrations including receptor overexpression, mutation, ligand‐depen- dent receptor dimerization, and ligand‐independent activa- tion.5 Activation of EGFR leads to autophosphorylation of TKs resulting in continuous activation of downstream signaling pathways involved in cancer progression.7 EGFR is a success‐proven target in treating patients with NSCLCs, that is, drugs targeting EGFR approved for use in the clinic that small molecules, natural products, and biologics.8 Of note, the 4‐anilinoquinazoline series are the most developed TKIs that were approved for treating lung and other cancer types,9-12 TKIs inhibit the active site occupied by adenosine triphosphate (ATP) within the intracellular domain that subsequently impedes conforma- tional changes to the protein hindering phosphorylation activities and downstream signaling. Erlotinib and gefitinib are competitive reversible TKIs that bind competitively against the ATP substrate to the active site.8,13 It was shown that competitive binding of TKIs led to cell apoptosis and decreased proliferation.14 Furthermore, it was revealed the two inhibitors, erlotinib and gefitinib, have significant responses upon dosing in lung adenocarcinomas15 and were approved for the second‐ and third‐line treatment of advanced lung cancer.16 However, drug resistance developed against erlotinib and gefitinib with the well‐known T790M EGFR: EGFR mutants with threonine to methionine

mutation at codon 790 (T790M) of exon 20 on the TK domain.4 T790M mutation occurs in ~50% of EGFR mutations. In addition, overlapping mutations in EGFR and KRAS genes have shown resistance in treating patients with NSCLCs.17 Irreversible TKIs with quinazoline‐based scaffolds were then developed primarily as a solution for the T790M mutation, for example, afatinib and osimertinib.8 The key feature of irreversible TKIs is seen by the presence of a Michael acceptor that accepts a nucleophilic cysteine residue to form a covalent adduct.18 Nevertheless, resistance against irreversible TKIs emerged as a result of a point mutation at codon 797 from cysteine to serine (C797S), which suggests there is still a need to search for novel EGFR inhibitors to overcome the problem of emerging EGFR mutants. Structure‐based virtual screening has shown successes in searching for novel inhibitors of well‐characterized protein targets, such as anaplastic lymphoma kinase inhibitor,19 cyclin‐dependent kinase 2 inhibitor from Chinese medi- cine,20 and HER2 inhibitor from natural products.21 This method is used for molecular docking to screen compound libraries in silico and to study the binding modes of the drug candidates. The method offered cost effectiveness and reduced time and laborious efforts to screen large compound libraries for active hits in vitro.22 In this study, our aim is to search for novel EGFR inhibitors using virtual screening in which virtual hits are validated in vitro for EGFR inhibition activities. We began the study by conducting a similarity search using a similarity coefficient of 0.95 on the PubChem database website (NIH, MD) based on eight starting compounds from our previous report.23 The activities of these eight compounds were benchmarked using the known EGFR inhibitor, gefitinib. The two most potent compounds were then further tested against the A549 cell line using a 96‐well–based cytotoxicity assay, cytotoxicity, and Wes- tern blot analysis.

| Compound ligand preparation Eight compounds (NSC351123, NSC130831, NSC299137, NSC135371, NSC48283, NSC306698, NSC402959, and NSC125910) from our previous virtual screening cam- paign were subjected as queries for the search of similar compounds with 95% structural similarity on the Pub- Chem database website (https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih. gov/). All similar compounds were downloaded in a PDF format for further docking. Tyrosine kinase inhibitors (TKIs) such as Erlotinib (Tarceva, OSI‐774; Genentech, South San Francisco, CA) and gefitinib (Iressa, ZD1839; AstraZeneca, Macclesfield, UK) were obtained for using as standard inhibitors. | M A T E R I A L S AN D M E T H O D S F I G U R E 1 Conceptual workflow demonstrated for selecting novel compound against kinase activity based computational analysis GOLD docking program version 4.0.124 was used for all docking experiments. The human EGFR crystal structure was obtained from the Protein Data Bank (PDB) coded 1M17. The protein structure was protonated and all water molecules were removed from the structure. Configura- tion parameters were set as default. The ChemScore kinase Fitness Function KSC was used for scoring and ranking the best compound. Interaction of EGFR‐TK and the candidate compounds were visualized by Discovery Studio Visualizer 2016 program (Accelrys Inc, San Diego, CA). A workflow diagram is shown in Figure 1.

2.3 inhibition and IC50 evaluation To test for activity, we used the EGFR‐TK from Millipore (Burlington, MA), Lot #31179U‐D and kinase activity is probed by the Antibody Beacon TK Assay Kit (Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA). TK samples were prepared in 1× kinase buffer containing 2 mM dithio- threitol (DTT). One hundred nanograms per microliters of TK enzyme was prepared and further diluted to 16 ng/ µL as the working concentration. Ten millimolar stock solution of screened compounds, gefitinib were sepa- rately prepared in 100% dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and Inhibition assay for relative kept at −20°C. Each stock solution of screened com- pounds and both inhibitors were diluted in 1× kinase buffer containing 2 mM DTT to 4 µM before performing the assay. The final concentration of DMSO in the solution was less than 0.1%. The antibody Beacon detection complex plus substrate was prepared according to the manufacturer’s instructions. In brief, the reaction buffer contained 62.5 nM Oregon Green 488 ligand, 125 nM anti‐phosphotyrosine antibody, 500 µg/mL TK substrate, and 1× kinase buffer plus 2 mM DTT.

To determine the relative inhibition, 12.5 µL of TK (final concentration, 4 ng/µL) was added with 12.5 µL of each compound samples (final concentration, 1 µM) to the 96‐well microplate (96‐well black flat bottom #3915; Corning, MA). The two components were mixed and incubated at room temperature for 10 minutes. The detection complex was added to the mixture and incubated for 10 minutes at 30°C. Only 1× kinase buffer plus 2 mM DTT was used as a negative control. To start the reaction,5 µL of 5 mM ATP was added to each well and the fluorescence intensity was measured for 1.5 hours at 485/535 nm by fluorescence spectroscopy (INFINITE F200 PRO; TECAN. Switzerland). The same protocol was repeated to calculate for the IC50 values with multiple concentrations of each compound −6 µM in 10‐fold dilution steps. varying from 100 µM to 1 × 10 Curve fitting was performed by using GraphPad PRISM, 6.0e (GraphPad Software, CA).

To study the cytotoxic effects of the compounds, 3‐(4, 5‐dimethylthiazol‐2‐yl)‐2,5‐diphenyltetrazolium bromide (MTT) assay was conducted.25 Human lung cancer cell line A549 (ATCC CCL‐185) cells were used for the determination of cell cytotoxicity. Cells were seeded in the complete DMEM medium in a 96‐well plate contain- ing 10% fetal bovine serum, 100 U/mL penicillin, and 100 U/mL streptomycin. Cells were cultured at 37°C in a humidified atmosphere with 5% CO2 overnight before the incubation, 70% to 80% experiment. After overnight confluence of the cells was cultured in the complete DMEM with different concentrations of the compounds (100, 50, 25, 12.5, 6.25, 3.125, 1.56, and 0.78 μM) for 72 hours. Each well was then replaced with a fresh medium containing MTT (5 mg/mL in phosphate‐buf- fered saline) and further incubated for 3 hours. This was followed by removal of the medium and 50 μL of DMSO was added to each well. The microplate containing treated cells was immediately shaken for 10 seconds and settled for 10 seconds before determining the dose response. The measurement was taken using a micro- plate reader at a wavelength of 570 nm. | Cell cytotoxicity assay The role of the compounds on apoptosis was subsequently evaluated, whether they have a dose‐ or time‐dependent function. After treatment, the treated cells were gently trypsinized. The harvested cells were incubated with annexin V and dead cell reagent for 20 minutes at room temperature before analyzed using cell analyzer MUSE (Merck‐MiIIipore, MA) according to the manufacturer’s instructions. All experiments were independently performed three times.

The treated cells were stimulated with 20 ng/mL of EGF in DMEM containing 1% FBS for 30 minutes before harvesting. The cells were lyzed with radioimmunoprecipitation assay buffer. The protein concentration was determined using the Bradford assay. Fifteen micrograms of lysates were separated with 12% sodium dodecyl sulfate polyacrylamide gel electro- phoresis. The separated proteins were transferred, blocked, and incubated with anti‐P‐Y1173 of EGFR (#44794G; Invitrogen, CA), anti‐EGFR (#4267; CST, MA), or antiactin (Thermo Fisher Scientific, MA) for 1 hour. Secondary antibodies were then incubated for detection. At the end of the incubation time, the membranes were developed with enhanced chemiluminescence substrate. All (≥3) independent experiments were done in triplicate, which was expressed as mean ± standard deviation. For IC50, statistical analysis was performed with nonlinear regression (curve fit) in log (inhibitor) vs response‐variable slope (four parameters) equation. For apoptosis assay, statistical analysis was performed with two‐way analysis of variance (ANOVA) and significant difference (P < 0.05) were determined using ANOVA with Tukey’s test. All statistical analysis was done using GraphPad 6.0 software (GraphPad Software, CA). We previously identified eight starting compounds from virtual screening23: NSC351123, NSC130831, NSC299137, NSC135371, NSC48283, NSC306698, NSC402959, and NSC125910 following conceptual workflow in Figure 1. Two hundred similar chemical structures resulted from similarity search on the PubChem database. These were docked against EGFR‐TK using the GOLD software. All 34 virtual hit compounds were experimentally tested against EGFR‐TK and the results were compared with gefitinib as shown in Figure 2. Six of the 34 compounds than 50% inhibition. The six chosen exhibited less compounds were nogalamycin N‐oxide (NSC116555), 1‐amino‐4‐[4‐(4‐amino‐2‐sulfophenyl)anilino]‐9,10‐dioxoan- thracene‐2‐sulfonic acid (NSC125910), (2‐phenylquinoline‐4‐ carbonyl)2‐phenylquinoline‐4‐carboxylate (NSC130831), N‐(9,10‐dioxoanthracen‐1‐yl)‐7‐oxobenzo[e]perimidine‐4‐car- boxamide (NSC299137), 1‐[hydroxy‐bis(4‐phenylphenyl) methyl]cyclohexan‐1‐ol (NSC351123), and 2,6‐diphenyl‐4‐(2‐ phenyl‐1,3,2‐dioxaborolan‐4‐yl)‐4,4a,8,8a‐tetrahydro‐[1,3,2]di- oxaborinino[5,4‐d][1,3,2]dioxaborinine (NSC48283) (Figure 3). The NSC116555 and NSC125910 were the most active compounds that exhibited over 90% inhibition against the EGFR‐TK under the assay condition (Table 1). The IC50 v alues of NSC125910 and NSC116555 were further determined by dose‐response curves and the IC50 values of both compounds were found to be 16.14 ± 0.77 and 37.71 ± 1.20 nM, respectively. These IC50 values corresponded to the two top‐scoring ChemScore docking values of 46.31 and 36.53, respectively.

To study the cytotoxicities of the six compounds, the the EGFR drug‐ compounds were tested against sensitive cancer cell line, A549. Gefitinib, a drug which had been approved for treatment of advanced NSCLC was used as the positive control. Herein, the A549 cell line was used as a model for insensitive‐TKI NSCLC cell line, which is a KRAS mutant (G12S) dependent.26 The IC50 values against line were determined (Table 1). NSC116555 was found to be the most potent compound against the A549 cell line with IC50 = 0.19 ± 0.01 µM, whereas gefitinib displayed the second best cytotoxic effect with IC50 = 26.27 ± 0.53 µ M. The remaining compounds, including NSC125910, showed IC50 values more than 100 µM. To study the effect of apoptosis induced by the NSC116555 compound, the compound was tested against the A549 cell line. The IC50 of the compound was used as the effect‐determining concentration throughout the experiment. Herein, the gefitinib inhibitor was used as the positive control (Figure 5). The cells were treated separately with NSC116555 and gefitinib; and after 24‐hour incubation, the total number of apoptotic cell populations increased by ~30% and 50%, respectively. The A549 cell was incubated with various concentration of NSC116555 (A‐F) for 24 hours. After the incubation time, the cells stained following the instructions demonstrated that NSC116555 increased apoptotic cell in a dose‐dependent manner. All experiments were done in triplicate died almost completely through apoptotic mechanisms. In contrast, NSC116555 did not induce apoptosis with the same concentration and increasing incubation durations did not affect cell death populations (Figure 6). However, apoptotic cell counts gradually increased with increasing concentration of NSC116555. Doxorubicin was used as positive control in a dose‐dependent manner experiment, which induced cell apoptosis at equivalent concentration when compared with NSC116555 (Supporting Informa- tion Figure 2). All experiments were done in triplicate. *P < 0.05, statistically significant | Binding mode of NSC116555 Molecular docking revealed that the NSC116555 binds deep within the ATP‐binding pocket of EGFR, forming similar hydrogen bond interactions comparable with that of gefitinib (Figure 7). NSC116555 formed binding interactions with threonine 854 in the DFG‐in conforma- tion with the kinase domain activation loop. Additional conserved hydrogen bond interactions with NSC116555 were also found including cysteine 797, alanine 743, lysine 745, aspartic acid 855, cysteine 797, leucine 844, aspartic acid 855, and phenylalanine 856. This resulted in drug tolerance in advanced‐NSCLC patient harboring EGFR mutants.29 Herein, we attempted to screen for novel EGFR inhibitors.

The virtual screening of NCI diversity set was used as a starting point to find a new chemical scaffold for TK inhibitor of EGFR. First eight candidates from pervious studies23 were used to find more similar structures resulting in 200 compounds that were docked against the EGFR target using GOLD. The hit compounds that have similar ChemScore to the well‐known inhibitors gefitinib, erlotinib, and lapatinib were subsequent in vitro screening. The result revealed two promising candidates: NSC125910 and NSC116555. Furthermore, the anti‐TK experiment showed IC50 values of both NSC125910 and NSC116555, which were similar to the gefitinib. The adenocarcinoma human alveolar basal epithelial cells, A549, were used to test for their cytotoxic effects. The IC50 values revealed that only NSC116555 had potent activity against the A549 cells (IC50 = 0.19 µM), whereas NSC125910 and other com- pounds showed much weaker potencies (IC50 > 100 µM). Since, the second‐generation of irreversible ATP‐analog inhibitor, afatinib30 was resistant to the C797S EGFR mutation in patients. This led us to ask if NSC116555 could be effective against this mutant. Our docking scores showed that NSC116555 could bind effectively on both wild‐type and C797S mutant with similar docking scores. This indicated that NSC116555 could be a potential inhibitor against C797S mutant too. Doxorubicin, an anticancer drug that acts by DNA intercalation,31 has similar structural features to the active NSC116555 leading us to ponder if it has similar the EGFR target. To clarify this, effects against doxorubicin was tested in vitro against the EGFR target. The result obtained showed doxorubicin did not affect EGFR phosphorylation. However, doxoru- bicin‐mediated EGFR family activation had been explored, which is an important survival response.32 (Supporting Information Figure 3). These findings suggested that NSC116555 could selectively attenuate EGFR phosphorylation related to the enzymatic kinase assay result.

According to molecular docking results, cell cytotoxi- city appeared to demonstrate that NSC116555 could be accommodated within the EGFR pocket, and had confirmed in vitro EGFR activity and also is a potent cytotoxic agent against NSCLC cell growth. The imbal- ance between cell division and cell death, called “apoptosis,” has always been a concern in many cancers. Consequently, unlimited cell division led to poor prog- nosis in cancer patients. In conclusion, our findings demonstrated that NSC116555 could induce cell death via apoptosis in a dose‐dependent manner. Moreover, at effect‐determining concentrations, NSC116555 is also more effective than gefitinib and is current for NSCLC. Hence, NSC116555 may serve as a promising lead for future EGFR‐expressing cancer cell research.
